post_text:
It is time! Finish your High School Journey with us.

Enrollment for the 2020-2021 school year is now open at the Pellerin Center.

The Pellerin Center enrolls students of all ages and offers multiple options of high school completion as well as GED prep classes and on-site GED testing (PearsonVue). On-line classes are available.

Space is limited, so please complete an online enrollment form to secure your orientation and enrollment date (Phoenix Days: August 18, 19 and 20).

On-line enrollments will be contacted to confirm receipt of the registration packet and provide orientation dates.

Enrollment Packets will be taken:
During the School Year: at each individual building

During Summer Recess: June 23, 2020 - August 14, 2020
Tuesday – Thursday @ 10:00 a.m. – 3:00 p.m.

We look forward to seeing you in August!

post_text:
The students at Green Elementary delivered bears yesterday to Children's Hospital in memory of Skylar, who passed from COVID, age 5.

The students raised the money to purchase the bears with the support from Holly Hutton of 99.5 Rob and Holly Show.
shared_text:
Holly Hutton
June 5 at 7:04 PM ·

Today I was honored to join with the Detroit Police Department and Mrs.Nebel and the students of Green Elementary to donate bears to the Children's Hospital of Michigan in memory of Skylar who passed away at 5years old from Covid. You may remember seeing her beautiful face in the news. Her mother is DPD and it was so good to meet her and her husband and hear all the special things about her little girl. Thank you to Mrs.Nebel, Mrs.Nelson snd her students for raising over $700 to buy teddy bears! Those bears coupled with my own donation and stuffies from the donation earlier this year with DOD meant we were able to make sure all 230 beds would get a cuddle buddy! #bearhugdetroit
text:

Today I was honored to join with the Detroit Police Department and Mrs.Nebel and the students of Green Elementary to donate bears to the Children's Hospital of Michigan in memory of Skylar who passed away at 5years old from Covid. You may remember seeing her beautiful face in the news. Her mother is DPD and it was so good to meet her and her husband and hear all the special things about her little girl. Thank you to Mrs.Nebel, Mrs.Nelson snd her students for raising over $700 to buy teddy bears! Those bears coupled with my own donation and stuffies from the donation earlier this year with DOD meant we were able to make sure all 230 beds would get a cuddle buddy! #bearhugdetroit

post_text: Congratulations to Bianca K, Alice P and Julia W on winning the Adcraft Club of Detroit $2000 award for their video "One Drink Changes Everything." This video was submitted to the Courageous Persuaders video competition and focuses on the dangers of drinking and driving. The students produced this video in conjunction with the Macomb Sheriff's department in a collaborative effort between the Pankow TV & Broadcast Media class, the Pankow Broadcast Journalism class and the Pankow Performing Arts Acting program. Congratulations!!!

post_text: The Pankow Auto Collision course takes numerous awards at Autorama!
shared_text:
The Pankow Center
March 4 at 9:59 AM ·

It was a great weekend at the 2020 Autorama! Last Friday, 60 automotive students including several past students, started the weekend with a field trip to the annual Detroit Autorama. The trip began with "Student Career Day," a pre-curser to the event, which allows the students to see the display cars before the show opens to the public at noon Friday.

As a team, Pankow Collision & Refinishing students entered two vehicles and took 2nd place with the 1975 CJ5 Jeep, and 4th place with the Grand Cherokee Jeep. Auto Technology students also entered a vehicle and took 5th place for a Jeep Wrangler.

Autorama is considered the world’s largest indoor custom car show and attracts some of the nicest show cars in the country. "It is a lot of fun to participate with other like minded car enthusiast.' Mr. Rich Stumpf, Automotive Collision Teacher

post_text: At Green Elementary, Mrs. Ward’s grade 4 classroom was inducted into the FBI Junior Special Agent training! The course lasts eight weeks and the students learn about one aspect of the FBI per week. Students receive information and instruction on how the FBI reviews evidence, SWAT team organization and preparation, physical fitness and health, reviewing finger prints and how the FBI focuses on a total team approach to solve problems and conduct investigations. Students all write an essay on their experience and 4 – 6 of them are selected and read at the FBI Junior Special Agent Graduation in April.

post_text: Magic at Middle School North Science classes!
shared_text:
L'Anse Creuse Middle School North
February 11 at 5:55 PM ·

L'Anse Creuse Public Schools
Did you hear about standing a broom on end – and how it only worked yesterday?! Some crazy myth about NASA and the tilt of the Earth maybe? Well Mrs. Boska’s science students wants to show you it worked today – and it will work every day of the year! It has to do with center of mass and not tilt of the Earth on one day (ummm- the tilt of the Earth hasn’t changed in billions of years anyways). Next trick will be with the vernal equinox and standing an egg on end. Try it today because it works every day of the year also. Happy exploring!

post_text: Congratulations to Pankow Performing Arts Acting teacher Kirk Erickson who in the final months of 2019 was awarded the Come From Kindness award from Broadway in Detroit who gave tickets to the musical Come from Away to the nominees. He also won the Unsung Hero Award from Art Van Furniture, recognizing unsung heroes in their community with a $1,000 gift card. He also finished the school year as the Festival Director for the 2019 Michigan Thespian Festival held for the first time in Detroit. Over 1700 students from around the state took part in the festival coordinated by Erickson. The students in the Pankow program earned close to $400,000 in scholarships at the festival.

A Note from Superintendent Erik Edoff:

Each and every day, the safety of students and staff remains the top priority of the district to ensure that we continually strive to provide a safe learning environment for everyone. In an effort to maintain the best environment for all, it is necessary to practice emergency drills throughout the year. With that being said, I would like to take a moment and share with you a video about a district wide safety drill that will take place on November 22, 2019 with all students and staff. Similar to other drills your children participate in throughout the year, this drill is also intended as practice in case of an emergency. Please take a minute to watch the video linked below, and feel free to contact your building principal with any questions.

Thank you and have a wonderful Thanksgiving holiday.

Erik Edoff
Superintendent

text:
A Note from Superintendent Erik Edoff:

Each and every day, the safety of students and staff remains the top priority of the district to ensure that we continually strive to provide a safe learning environment for everyone. In an effort to maintain the best environment for all, it is necessary to practice emergency drills throughout the year. With that being said, I would like to take a moment and share with you a video about a district wide safety drill that will take place on November 22, 2019 with all students and staff. Similar to other drills your children participate in throughout the year, this drill is also intended as practice in case of an emergency. Please take a minute to watch the video linked below, and feel free to contact your building principal with any questions.

Thank you and have a wonderful Thanksgiving holiday.

Erik Edoff
Superintendent

post_text: Mayor Terry Stoneburner presented an Algonac Asset Award to Green Elementary staff member, Robyn Rivard, on behalf of the Cory Rivard, Jr. Promise Foundation. The Foundation recently purchased a bike Fixit maintenance station for the Algonac Lions Field. The Fixit includes all the tools necessary to perform basic bike repairs and maintenance. The Cory Rivard, Jr. Promise Foundation, is named in memory of Cory Rivard, and was created to promote public awareness about and prevention of suicide. Josh Rivard credits his brother Cory with introducing him to cycling and felt that the bike station was a fitting way to pay quiet homage to him.

Over the summer Jennifer Allen, L'Anse Creuse High School French Teacher, flew out to Los Angeles to be a contestant on the Wheel of Fortune! She auditioned at the Wheelmobile event at the Aretha Franklin amphitheater in mid May, was called back for a second audition in June and was selected to be a contestant on the show just a few weeks later. According to Allen: "It’s been an absolute blast and a dream come true!!!"

Tune in to WDIV Local 4 on Monday, November 11th, at 7pm to cheer on our L'Anse Creuse High School teacher on Wheel of Fortune!!!

post_text: Last week students from the Broadcast Journalism class were interviewed by Carolyn Clifford from Channel 7 News at the National Association of Media Literacy in Education conference at Wayne State University. As a participating school in PBS Student Reporting Labs, these students also served as leaders at the conference for students attending from across the state, teaching them how to become better broadcasters and strengthen their journalism skills. Later that week PBS NewsHour Student Reporting Labs producers, Briget Ganske and Elis Estrada visited the CreuseLine set to share their insights on creating stronger interviews.

post_text: Students at the FV Pankow Center visited a number of manufacturers today as they attended the annual Macomb County Event "Manufacturing Day." The students here visited Alba Tooling and Engineering learning how molds are created for car parts and having an opportunity to create their own mold injections using their injection machines. The students featured here, documented the event on film for the MFG Day Video Competition as a part of the Pankow Broadcast Journalism program. A film of today's event will be finished in about a month where you can see the students in action and learn more about this incredible event.

post_text: Higgins Elementary is starting something new to increase social emotional learning. Each K-5 student has been assigned to a small multiage group called a Hawk’s Nest. Each Hawk Nest is led by a staff member for the purpose of building a community of people who work together to build relationships, trust, a sense of belonging and to promote kindness across the grade levels. Students will meet with Hawk Nest group monthly for about 40 minutes. The first meeting was a huge success! The older students LOVED helping the younger students find their way around the school! It was truly a wonderful display of kindness!!

Dear Parents/Guardians:

Today, as a precautionary measure, the DiAnne M. Pellerin Center and the Frederick V. Pankow Center were on a brief external lockdown due to a student issue at the nearby DiAnne M. Pellerin Center. Upon investigation, it was quickly confirmed that this was a case of mistaken identity and deemed there was no danger to students or staff. We take this opportunity to keep you as the parent/guardian informed and want to reassure you that no student was at risk. We treat every incident seriously and your child’s safety is our top priority.

post_text:
Many of you have been interested in the 2019-2020 School Calendar. While the full calendar is still in the negotiation process, the district has been able to lock in some of the important dates. For your planning purposes, we have attached a preliminary calendar with the first and last day of school, winter break, spring break and more.

Please note that this calendar only specifies holidays and breaks; the district will be adding early release days for professional development, conferences, and the end of marking periods.

When a full calendar is completed we will be sure to send it out to families.

post_text:
The LCPS Support Services Department recently hosted their annual Crawford Awards to honor our fantastic support staff! The staff awarded were (in order of the pictures):

- Denise Thiry-Williford and Sue Olesky were honored for 30 years of service
- LiAnn Fackler was honored for 20 years of service
- Lori Jarvis received the Henry Crawford Driver of the Year Award
- Russell Holdwick was named Special Needs Driver of the Year
- Abe Jenkins received the Good Wrench Award for keeping his bus clean, writing up all mechanical issues and performing preventative maintenance promptly throughout the school year

Congratulations to all!
